					<description><![CDATA[<p>Paris-based voice AI startup Gradium has announced a major $100 million seed funding round. The company recently added a $30 million extension to its initial $70 million tranche raised last</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/voice-ai-startup-gradium-raises-100m-seed/" data-wpel-link="internal">Voice AI Startup Gradium Raises $100M Seed for Global Expansion</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Paris-based voice AI startup Gradium has </span><a href="https://gradium.ai/blog/gradium-100-million-funding-nvidia" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">announced</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400"> a major $100 million seed funding round. The company recently added a $30 million extension to its initial $70 million tranche raised last December. Tech giant Nvidia joined the round as the headline investor. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Gradium raises $100M to push its voice AI into its next major growth phase. It highlights the growing enterprise demand for real-time audio systems. Global investors are betting heavily on this specific team’s deep technical expertise. The fresh capital will directly fuel global expansion and aggressive talent acquisition.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">NVIDIA Joins the $100 Million Seed Tranche</span></h2>
<div id="attachment_203483" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-203483" class="size-large wp-image-203483" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Gradium-NVIDIA-1024x463.jpg" alt="Minimalist dark blue graphic featuring the corporate white logos of Gradium and NVIDIA side-by-side, accented by a glowing multi-colored 3D wave composed of digital particle points." width="1024" height="463" /><p id="caption-attachment-203483" class="wp-caption-text">Gradium and NVIDIA Partnership</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Gradium’s expanded seed round shows intense investor confidence. The latest $30 million extension officially brought Nvidia into the fold. The original $70 million round in December 2025 saw heavy backing from top venture firms. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">FirstMark Capital and Eurazeo led that initial phase. Other prominent backers included DST Global Partners, Korelya Capital, and Amplify Partners. High-profile individual investors also joined. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Former Google CEO Eric Schmidt and French billionaires Xavier Niel and Rodolphe Saadé backed the startup early on. Gradium has kept its current valuation private. The massive capital pool gives them a significant runway to challenge established tech giants in the artificial intelligence sector.</span></p>
<p><b><i>More Updates: </i></b><a href="https://ventureburn.com/databento-raises-97m-series-b-crypto-market-data/" data-wpel-link="internal"><b><i>Databento Raises $97M in Series B To Expand Institutional-Grade Market Data</i></b></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">The Minds Behind Modern Voice AI</span></h2>
<div id="attachment_203484" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-203484" class="size-large wp-image-203484" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/founders_1-1024x683.jpg" alt="The four founders of Paris-based voice AI startup Gradium—Alexandre Defossez, Laurent Mazaré, Neil Zeghidour, and Olivier Teboul—smiling and sitting side-by-side on a wooden bench inside a rustic workshop studio." width="1024" height="683" /><p id="caption-attachment-203484" class="wp-caption-text">Founders: Image Credit: Gradium</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The startup spun out of the French non-profit research lab Kyutai just seven months ago. Gradium’s four co-founders are highly respected figures in the global AI community. Chief Executive Officer Neil Zeghidour previously conducted research at Meta and Google DeepMind. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The Chief Science Officer Alexandre Défossez co-created EnCodec at Meta’s FAIR lab. Laurent Mazaré, Chief Coding Officer, brings deep engineering experience from DeepMind and Jane Street. Chief Technology Officer Olivier Teboul previously worked at Google Brain. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Together, this team authored the foundational research papers for EnCodec, SoundStream, and Moshi. These technologies underpin many modern voice systems used today. Their unique history gives Gradium a distinct competitive edge over newer rivals.</span></p>
<p><b><i>More Updates: </i></b><a href="https://ventureburn.com/gim-raises-us20-million-ai-investment-platform/" data-wpel-link="internal"><b><i>GIM Raises US$20 Million to Advance AI Investment Systems</i></b></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Setting New Standards in Audio Technology</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Gradium focuses on building ultra-low latency audio-native AI models. Traditional voice tools often suffer from annoying conversational delays. Gradium solves this by creating real-time multilingual transcription and speech synthesis software. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Their tools allow developers to build seamless conversational interfaces. The global AI voice market is expanding rapidly. It is projected to grow from billions today to over twenty billion dollars by 2031. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Gradium is already proving its enterprise value in the real world. The startup has already signed major corporate clients. For instance, French automaker Renault is using their technology to power next-generation in-car voice experiences.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Scaling Globally from Paris to the Bay Area</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The new capital will primarily fund Gradium’s aggressive global expansion plans. While the core research team remains in Paris, the company is opening a new office in the San Francisco Bay Area. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This strategic move helps Gradium compete directly for top-tier machine learning talent in Silicon Valley. The hiring push will focus heavily on engineers and product experts. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Expanding to the United States positions Gradium to better serve international enterprise clients. They will directly compete with major players like ElevenLabs and Google Gemini. This funding ensures they have the resources to scale infrastructure and win global market share.</span></p>
